bitLength.name: bitLength
bitLength.comment:
Returns the minimum number of bits required to store this integer.

The number of bits excludes the sign bit, which gives the natural length for non-negative (unsigned) values. Negative values are complemented to return the bit position of the first bit that differs from the sign bit.

To find the the number of bits needed to store the value as a signed value, add one, i.e. use x.bitLength + 1.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides fixnum/fixnum.IntX.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

isEven.name: isEven
isEven.comment: Returns true if and only if this integer is even.

isMaxValue.name: isMaxValue
isMaxValue.comment: Returns true if and only if this integer is the maximum signed value that can be represented within its bit size.

isMinValue.name: isMinValue
isMinValue.comment: Returns true if and only if this integer is the minimum signed value that can be represented within its bit size.

isNegative.name: isNegative
isNegative.comment: Returns true if and only if this integer is less than zero.

isOdd.name: isOdd
isOdd.comment: Returns true if and only if this integer is odd.

isZero.name: isZero
isZero.comment: Returns true if and only if this integer is zero.

%.comment:
Euclidean modulo operator.

Returns the remainder of the euclidean division. The euclidean division of two integers a and b yields two integers q and r such that a == b * q + r and 0 <= r < a.abs().

<<.comment:
Left bit-shift operator.

Returns the result of shifting the bits of this integer by fixnum/fixnum.IntX.<<.shiftAmount bits to the left. Low-order bits are filled with zeros.

<=.comment: Relational less than or equal to operator.

==.comment: Returns true if and only if fixnum/fixnum.IntX.==.other is an int or IntX equal in value to this integer.

>=.comment: Relational greater than or equal to operator.

>>.comment:
Right bit-shift operator.

Returns the result of shifting the bits of this integer by fixnum/fixnum.IntX.>>.shiftAmount bits to the right. High-order bits are filled with zero in the case where this integer is positive, or one in the case where it is negative.

unary-.name: unary-
unary-.comment:
Negate operator.

Note that -MIN_VALUE is equal to MIN_VALUE due to overflow.

abs.name: abs
abs.comment: Returns the absolute value of this integer.

clamp.name: clamp
clamp.comment: Clamps this integer to be in the range fixnum/fixnum.IntX.clamp.lowerLimit - fixnum/fixnum.IntX.clamp.upperLimit.

compareTo.name: compareTo
compareTo.comment:
Compares this object to another dart-core.Comparable

Returns a value like a dart-core.Comparator when comparing this to fixnum/fixnum.IntX.compareTo.other. That is, it returns a negative integer if this is ordered before fixnum/fixnum.IntX.compareTo.other, a positive integer if this is ordered after fixnum/fixnum.IntX.compareTo.other, and zero if this and fixnum/fixnum.IntX.compareTo.other are ordered together.

The fixnum/fixnum.IntX.compareTo.other argument must be a value that is comparable to this object.

numberOfLeadingZeros.name: numberOfLeadingZeros
numberOfLeadingZeros.comment: Returns the number of high-order zeros in this integer's bit representation.

numberOfTrailingZeros.name: numberOfTrailingZeros
numberOfTrailingZeros.comment: Returns the number of low-order zeros in this integer's bit representation.

remainder.name: remainder
remainder.comment: Returns the remainder of the truncating division of this integer by fixnum/fixnum.IntX.remainder.other.

shiftRightUnsigned.name: shiftRightUnsigned
shiftRightUnsigned.comment:
Unsigned right-shift operator.

Returns the result of shifting the bits of this integer by fixnum/fixnum.IntX.shiftRightUnsigned.shiftAmount bits to the right. High-order bits are filled with zeros.

toBytes.name: toBytes
toBytes.comment:
Returns a byte-sequence representation of this integer.

Returns a list of int, starting with the least significant byte.

toDouble.name: toDouble
toDouble.comment:
Returns the double representation of this integer.

On some platforms, inputs with large absolute values (i.e., > 2^52) may lose some of their low-order bits.

toHexString.name: toHexString
toHexString.comment: Returns a string representing the value of this integer in hexadecimal notation; example: '0xd'.

toInt.name: toInt
toInt.comment:
Returns the int representation of this integer.

On some platforms, inputs with large absolute values (i.e., > 2^52) may lose some of their low-order bits.

toInt32.name: toInt32
toInt32.comment:
Returns an Int32 representation of this integer.

Narrower values are sign-extended and wider values have their high bits truncated.

toInt64.name: toInt64
toInt64.comment: Returns an Int64 representation of this integer.

toRadixString.name: toRadixString
toRadixString.comment:
Returns a string representing the value of this integer in the given radix.

fixnum/fixnum.IntX.toRadixString.radix must be an integer in the range 2 .. 16, inclusive.

toSigned.name: toSigned
toSigned.comment:
Returns the least significant fixnum/fixnum.IntX.toSigned.width bits of this integer, extending the highest retained bit to the sign. This is the same as truncating the value to fit in fixnum/fixnum.IntX.toSigned.width bits using an signed 2-s complement representation. The returned value has the same bit value in all positions higher than fixnum/fixnum.IntX.toSigned.width.

If the input value fits in fixnum/fixnum.IntX.toSigned.width bits without truncation, the result is the same as the input. The minimum width needed to avoid truncation of x is x.bitLength + 1, i.e.

x == x.toSigned(x.bitLength + 1);

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representing the value of this integer in decimal notation; example: '13'.

toUnsigned.name: toUnsigned
toUnsigned.comment:
Returns the least significant fixnum/fixnum.IntX.toUnsigned.width bits of this integer as a non-negative number (i.e. unsigned representation). The returned value has zeros in all bit positions higher than fixnum/fixnum.IntX.toUnsigned.width.

If the input fits in fixnum/fixnum.IntX.toUnsigned.width bits without truncation, the result is the same as the input. The minimum width needed to avoid truncation of x is given by x.bitLength, i.e.

x == x.toUnsigned(x.bitLength);

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides fixnum/fixnum.IntX.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and fixnum/fixnum.IntX.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the fixnum/fixnum.IntX.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

compareTo.name: compareTo
compareTo.comment:
Compares this object to another dart-core.Comparable

Returns a value like a dart-core.Comparator when comparing this to fixnum/fixnum.IntX.compareTo.other. That is, it returns a negative integer if this is ordered before fixnum/fixnum.IntX.compareTo.other, a positive integer if this is ordered after fixnum/fixnum.IntX.compareTo.other, and zero if this and fixnum/fixnum.IntX.compareTo.other are ordered together.

The fixnum/fixnum.IntX.compareTo.other argument must be a value that is comparable to this object.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
fixnum/fixnum.IntX.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to fixnum/fixnum.IntX.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If fixnum/fixnum.IntX.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of fixnum/fixnum.IntX.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.
